<div class="header">
<h1>Ideal Societies</h1>
<div class="subtitle">Research & Writing Companion — Summative Assessment</div>
<p class="intro">This page has everything you need for your research paper: the sources to draw from, the structure to follow, and tips for writing each section. Work through the tabs below.</p>
</div>

<nav class="nav-tabs" role="tablist">
<button class="nav-tab active" role="tab" data-tab="priorities" aria-selected="true">Your Direction</button>
<button class="nav-tab" role="tab" data-tab="sources" aria-selected="false">Sources</button>
<button class="nav-tab" role="tab" data-tab="writing" aria-selected="false">Writing Guide</button>
<button class="nav-tab" role="tab" data-tab="citations" aria-selected="false">Citations</button>
</nav>

<!-- ========== TAB 1: PRIORITIES ========== -->

<div class="panel active" id="panel-priorities">
<div class="card">
<h2>Choose Your Priority</h2>
<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">Your research paper will argue which factors matter most for creating an ideal society. To get started, choose a <strong>priority question</strong> that interests you. This becomes the lens for your research — it shapes your research question, the evidence you collect, and the argument you make.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom:1.5rem; color:var(--muted); font-size:0.92rem;">You are not locked into one of these. They're starting points to help focus your thinking. You can also combine elements or go your own way.</p>

```
<div class="priority-card freedom">
<span class="priority-label freedom">Individual Freedoms</span>
<div class="priority-question">What if the priority is protecting individual freedoms?</div>
<div class="priority-desc">Connects to: participation, citizen voice, free press, democracy, transparency. Think about societies that prioritise the right to speak, vote, protest, and make personal choices. What do they gain — and what challenges do they face?</div>
</div>

<div class="priority-card equality">
<span class="priority-label equality">Equal Outcomes</span>
<div class="priority-question">What if the priority is ensuring equal outcomes?</div>
<div class="priority-desc">Connects to: equity, fairness, standard of living, health, education. Think about societies that invest heavily in reducing gaps between rich and poor, providing universal services, and redistributing wealth. What trade-offs exist?</div>
</div>

<div class="priority-card survival">
<span class="priority-label survival">Long-Term Survival</span>
<div class="priority-question">What if the priority is long-term survival?</div>
<div class="priority-desc">Connects to: sustainability, resilience, innovation, environmental performance. Think about societies that build around climate action, resource management, and planning for the future. What do they sacrifice in the short term?</div>
</div>

<div class="priority-card stability">
<span class="priority-label stability">Stability & Security</span>
<div class="priority-question">What if the priority is stability and security?</div>
<div class="priority-desc">Connects to: governance, accountability, rule of law, anti-corruption, social trust. Think about societies that focus on strong institutions, low corruption, and reliable systems. What risks come with prioritising order?</div>
</div>

<div class="own-direction">
<h3>Have a different direction?</h3>
<p style="margin-top:0.5rem; font-size:0.95rem;">If you want to explore a different priority — like <em>cultural identity</em>, <em>technological innovation</em>, <em>social trust</em>, or something else — discuss it with your teacher. You can still use the sources on this page, just through a different lens.</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h2>From Priority to Research Question</h2>
<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">Your priority helps you write a strong research question. A good research question is <strong>specific</strong>, <strong>arguable</strong>, and <strong>researchable</strong>.</p>

<div class="tip-box">
<div class="tip-title">Examples of strong research questions</div>
<p style="margin-top:0.3rem; font-size:0.92rem;"><strong>Freedoms:</strong> "To what extent does press freedom contribute to higher quality of life in democratic societies?"</p>
<p style="font-size:0.92rem;"><strong>Equality:</strong> "How does reducing income inequality affect health and education outcomes in Scandinavian countries?"</p>
<p style="font-size:0.92rem;"><strong>Survival:</strong> "Why do some countries achieve both high environmental performance and high human development, while others do not?"</p>
<p style="font-size:0.92rem;"><strong>Stability:</strong> "How does corruption affect citizens' trust in government and overall societal well-being?"</p>
</div>

<div class="warning-box">
<div class="warning-title">Avoid questions like these</div>
<p style="margin-top:0.3rem; font-size:0.92rem;">"What is an ideal society?" — too broad, not arguable.<br>
"Is Finland a good country?" — yes/no questions don't generate analysis.<br>
"What are the factors of an ideal society?" — this is a list, not an argument.</p>
</div>
</div>
```

</div>

