<!-- ========== TAB 3: WRITING GUIDE ========== -->

<div class="panel" id="panel-writing">
<div class="card">
<h2>Your Paper Structure</h2>
<p style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Your paper follows a social science research structure. This means you present your <strong>evidence</strong> and your <strong>argument</strong> in separate sections — first you show what you found, then you discuss what it means.</p>
<p style="font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--muted);">Click each section below to see what goes in it and example sentence starters.</p>
</div>

```
<!-- Section 1: Introduction -->
<div class="section-scaffold">
<div class="section-header" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
<div style="display:flex; align-items:center;">
<span class="section-number">1</span>
<span class="section-title">Introduction</span>
<span class="section-criteria">B.i</span>
</div>
<span class="chevron">▼</span>
</div>
<div class="section-body">
<div class="section-content">
<div class="section-purpose">
<strong>Purpose:</strong> Tell the reader what your paper is about. State your research question, explain why it matters, and briefly preview your approach. This is also where your examiner sees your research question (Criterion B.i).
</div>
<div class="starters-label">Sentence starters</div>
<div class="starter"><span>This paper investigates</span> [your research question in full].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>This question matters because</span> understanding which factors contribute most to an ideal society helps us evaluate [what?]...</div>
<div class="starter"><span>Throughout this unit, we have explored</span> factors such as [list 3-4 factors from class]. This paper focuses specifically on [your priority/angle]...</div>
<div class="starter"><span>To investigate this question, I examined data from</span> [name 2-3 key sources] and compared [what you compared].</div>
<div class="tip-box">
<div class="tip-title">Length guide</div>
<p style="font-size:0.9rem;">About half a page. Four to six sentences. Don't start arguing yet — just set the scene.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Section 2: Background -->
<div class="section-scaffold">
<div class="section-header" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
<div style="display:flex; align-items:center;">
<span class="section-number">2</span>
<span class="section-title">Background</span>
<span class="section-criteria">D.i</span>
</div>
<span class="chevron">▼</span>
</div>
<div class="section-body">
<div class="section-content">
<div class="section-purpose">
<strong>Purpose:</strong> Give the reader the context they need to understand your argument. Explain the key concepts, define important terms, and show how your priority connects to the bigger picture of what makes a society "ideal." This is where Criterion D.i (analysing concepts) lives.
</div>
<div class="starters-label">Sentence starters</div>
<div class="starter"><span>An "ideal society" can be understood as</span> one in which [your working definition, drawing on factors from the unit].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>The concept of [your key concept, e.g., equity/participation/sustainability] refers to</span> [clear definition in your own words].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>Measuring development is complex because</span> indices like the HDI capture [what they capture] but miss [what they miss]...</div>
<div class="starter"><span>This paper focuses on [your priority] because</span> [why this factor/set of factors deserves attention].</div>
<div class="tip-box">
<div class="tip-title">Key move here</div>
<p style="font-size:0.9rem;">Use the conceptual vocabulary from this unit accurately. Terms like <em>equity, governance, resilience, sustainability, participation</em> — show you understand them, don't just drop them in.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Section 3: Evidence / Findings -->
<div class="section-scaffold">
<div class="section-header" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
<div style="display:flex; align-items:center;">
<span class="section-number">3</span>
<span class="section-title">Evidence / Findings</span>
<span class="section-criteria">B.iii</span>
</div>
<span class="chevron">▼</span>
</div>
<div class="section-body">
<div class="section-content">
<div class="section-purpose">
<strong>Purpose:</strong> Present the information you found in your research. This section <strong>reports</strong> — it does not argue. Organise your evidence by theme or factor, not by source. Include specific data: numbers, rankings, comparisons, and examples. Cite every piece of evidence.
</div>
<div class="starters-label">Sentence starters</div>
<div class="starter"><span>According to [source name],</span> [country] ranks [Xth] in [index] with a score of [number] (Author/Org, Year).</div>
<div class="starter"><span>The data shows that countries with higher levels of [factor]</span> tend to also have [what pattern?] (Source, Year).</div>
<div class="starter"><span>For example,</span> [specific country] has a [metric] of [value], compared to [other country]'s [value] (Source, Year).</div>
<div class="starter"><span>A notable pattern is that</span> [describe a trend or contrast you noticed across your sources].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>However, [country/region] is an exception:</span> despite [having X], it [does/doesn't Y] (Source, Year).</div>
<div class="warning-box">
<div class="warning-title">The most common mistake</div>
<p style="font-size:0.9rem;">Students mix evidence and opinion in this section. Save your analysis for the Discussion. Here, just tell the reader <em>what the data says</em>. Think of yourself as a reporter, not a debater.</p>
</div>
<div class="tip-box">
<div class="tip-title">Organisation tip</div>
<p style="font-size:0.9rem;">Use sub-headings to group your evidence. For example, if your priority is equality, you might have sub-headings like: "Income inequality," "Access to healthcare," and "Educational outcomes."</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Section 4: Discussion -->
<div class="section-scaffold">
<div class="section-header" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
<div style="display:flex; align-items:center;">
<span class="section-number">4</span>
<span class="section-title">Discussion</span>
<span class="section-criteria">D.ii + D.iv</span>
</div>
<span class="chevron">▼</span>
</div>
<div class="section-body">
<div class="section-content">
<div class="section-purpose">
<strong>Purpose:</strong> This is your argument. Explain what the evidence <em>means</em>. Which factors matter most for your chosen priority, and why? What are the trade-offs? What would someone who chose a different priority say? This is where Criterion D.ii (making arguments) and D.iv (multiple perspectives) live. This is the most important section.
</div>
<div class="starters-label">Sentence starters — making your argument (D.ii)</div>
<div class="starter"><span>The evidence suggests that [factor] is essential because</span> without it, [what happens?].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>The strongest argument for prioritising [your priority] is that</span> [main claim, supported by specific evidence from Section 3].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>While [factor A] clearly matters, the data shows that [factor B]</span> has a stronger relationship with [outcome], as demonstrated by [evidence].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>A key trade-off is that</span> prioritising [X] can sometimes come at the cost of [Y]. For example, [specific example].</div>

<div class="starters-label" style="margin-top:1rem;">Sentence starters — other perspectives (D.iv)</div>
<div class="starter"><span>Someone who prioritises [different priority] might argue that</span> [their strongest point]. This is a valid concern because [why].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>However, this perspective does not fully account for</span> [what it misses], as shown by [evidence].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>It is important to acknowledge that</span> different societies may define "ideal" differently depending on [their context, history, values].</div>

<div class="tip-box">
<div class="tip-title">What separates good from great</div>
<p style="font-size:0.9rem;">A good discussion makes a clear argument with evidence. A <em>great</em> discussion also acknowledges the best counter-argument and explains why your position still holds. Don't dismiss other views — engage with them honestly.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Section 5: Conclusion -->
<div class="section-scaffold">
<div class="section-header" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
<div style="display:flex; align-items:center;">
<span class="section-number">5</span>
<span class="section-title">Conclusion</span>
<span class="section-criteria">D.ii</span>
</div>
<span class="chevron">▼</span>
</div>
<div class="section-body">
<div class="section-content">
<div class="section-purpose">
<strong>Purpose:</strong> Answer your research question directly. Summarise your main argument and the key evidence that supports it. End with a final thought — a remaining question, a limitation of your research, or a connection to the bigger picture.
</div>
<div class="starters-label">Sentence starters</div>
<div class="starter"><span>This paper has argued that</span> [restate your central claim in one sentence].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>The evidence from [2-3 key sources] demonstrates that</span> [brief summary of your strongest points].</div>
<div class="starter"><span>While no society can be truly "ideal,"</span> this research suggests that [what?] are the most important foundations.</div>
<div class="starter"><span>A limitation of this research is that</span> [what couldn't you fully explore?]. Future investigation could examine [what?].</div>
<div class="tip-box">
<div class="tip-title">Length guide</div>
<p style="font-size:0.9rem;">About half a page. Don't introduce new evidence here — this is a wrap-up, not a new argument.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Section 6: References -->
<div class="section-scaffold">
<div class="section-header" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
<div style="display:flex; align-items:center;">
<span class="section-number">6</span>
<span class="section-title">References</span>
<span class="section-criteria">B.iii</span>
</div>
<span class="chevron">▼</span>
</div>
<div class="section-body">
<div class="section-content">
<div class="section-purpose">
<strong>Purpose:</strong> List every source you cited in your paper. See the Citations tab for formatting help.
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

